review_blob: 355ml can from the beer store. pours straw yellow with lively carbonation. Frothy white head with surprisingly good retention and lacing.Aroma contains strong metalic notes, corn, hay. light thin body with lively carbonation. mildly sweet (brewing sugar?) mild bitterness. abrupt finish. Meh. I prefer the 5.5. Thats not saying much though...

341 ml bottle from the beer store. pours clear copper with average carbonation. Frothy instantly disappearing white head that settles to a small rim, very minimal lacing. vague aroma of raspberries--a sweet nutty aroma not very gainy/malty but some notable wheat malt. slight caramel, Taste medium sweetness, non-bitter, light body, thin feel. Not bad for the beer store but otherwise nothing special
750ml bottle from the LCBO. Pours hazy yellow with a standard white head. Aroma of spice, citrus, grains and hops and yeast. taste is somewhat dry for the style. Good.
beer_name: Ommegang Game of Thrones #1 - Iron Throne Ale

review_blob: 473 ml can from LCBO. pours clear straw yellow with a frothy white head. not much carbonation. Aroma of grains straw, and a bit of hops. some metalic notes Nothing special.
341ml Bottle from Against the Grain (Toronto). pours hazy copper with some visible yeast. Aroma of fruit, malt, distinctive unibroue yeast. flavour is moderate sweet with long duration. Nice!

473ml can from the LCBO. Pours clear amber with a small white head that dissipates to a long lasting off white blanket. Average lacing. Aroma of hops and caramel malt. Taste is not overly bitter and finish is moderately smooth with mild bitterness. Not bad.
can. pours clear yellow. grainy. metallic, grassy aroma. They only thing this beers got going for it is its cheap...
bottle from the beer store. Pours light yellow aroma of malt, grainy, thin bodied with light carbonation. flavour is sweet. no metallic notes, no hops. Not a bad macro-style beer. inexpensive.
473 ml can from the seasonal pack. pours clear yellow with an average white head. aroma of malt, cardboard, metal. No good.
473 ml can. pours clear gold with average white head. Aroma of grains, malts, and some grassy and metallic notes. Meh.
473 ml can. Pours golden yellow with a decent sized white head. Aroma of lightly roasted malts, caramel, and grains and a bit of sour funk. Decent.
Bottle from the beer store. Aroma of lemon, wheat, and citrus. Pours clowdy medium blond. taste is very sweet. medium bodied. not bad.

500ml bottle. pours clear yellow with minimal visible carbonation. good lacing average lasting white head. Aroma is weak with metallic and grassy notes. flavour is moderate sweet mildly bitter. underwhelming
clear bottle. Pours clear light yellow. small white head. Aroma of grain, cardboard, skunk, corn. light bodied. boring.

Can. Pours light yellow with a clear white head. Was expecting some red/blue/orange. Nope--Just standard lager colouring. Aroma of (artificial) blueberries and sugar. Overpowering. Interesting sort of "Jolly Rancher" blueberry flavour too it, but overall a disappointment.

473ml can from Cest What? Pours black with a large creamy tan head. Aroma is dominated by freshly ground coffee a bit of hops and a small amount of caramel malt and an even smaller amount of vanilla. Medium carbonated smooth body. All around a "good" beer, but what a wonderful job with the coffee! Blown away by the full strength no holding back coffee.
beer_name: Wellington Welly One-Off Morning Brew Coffee Cream Stout

review_blob: March 14, on tap at Volo. pours dark brown with a light beige head. aroma of light roasted chocolate malt, . smooth. quite nice.
750ml swing-top bottle. Pours dark red-amber with an off white head. Quite a bit of hops in the aroma, toffee and light citrus combined with a bit of malt. medium body and surprisingly hoppy.

bottle. pours light gold with a hint of orange. creamy off white head. Aroma of hops, grapefruit and a bit of pine , some citrus. taste is smooth (for an IPA) with some sweet notes. similar to Mad Tom but Id say twice as good.
beer_name: Muskoka Twice As Mad Tom IPA

review_blob: bottle. pours golden orange/amber with aroma of grapefruit and caramel with good lacing. Very strong hops some pine. fairly bitter and dry. Nice.
can. pours clear light yellow with a surprisingly large foamy white head. aroma of hops,grain, grass and some metallic notes. Crisp and dry. Pretty good for a "light" beer.
Pours golden/orange. nose of grapefruit and hops. medium bodied with a bit of malt. Okay.
355ml bottle. Clear medium orange with frothy off white head with average lacing. Aroma of sweet medium bitter hops, soft carbonation and sweet malty base. Medium dry finish. Very refreshing

473 can. pours clear almond brown. Aroma of mint, vanilla, sugar, malt, caramel. medium bodied. taste is sweet with minimal bitterness. low carbonation. I really enjoyed the mint and vanilla. Pleasantly surprised by this one.

440 ml can. Pours dark brown/black with a creamy tan head. aroma of coffee, vanilla, roasted malt, and a small amount of smoke and chocolate. palate is creamy and taste is dry. Quite nice. Had this on tap about a year ago and thought it was too watery. This sample was great though.
600ml bottle. pours hazy golden orange with a small white head. Aroma of yeast, coriander, wheat, lemon  straw and grains, dry spice. grainy.Not bad
Bottle. pours dark brown, minimal beige head. aroma of dark fruit, alcohol, spice, and a little bit of yeast and a hint of smoke. taste is sweet. nice.

473ml can. 4.0%ABV pours mostly clear yellow with a frothy white head that dissipates fairly quick. weakly carbonated. Aroma of green apple jolly rancher that just fills the room. Despite the jolly rancher flavour which one might expect from a wine cooler, the backbone is composed of grainy straw like malts and no noticeable hops. A cross between a wine cooler, beer and a cider. Positives? its refreshing and anyone who doesnt regularly like beer may enjoy this. On the other hand, id much prefer a regular beer or a cider....
Bottle. pours medium golden orange with a frothy white head. good lacing. Aroma is dominated by hops, citrus, pine and a small amount of caramel. taste is very dry. powerful but wasnt for me.
bottle. "Bard*s". clear yellow with a small white head. aroma of grain. some, hay and caramel and of course sorgham. not bad. one of the better sorgham beers Ive had.

can. consumed from the can. pretty generic malt, grain, minimal hops. nothing wrong with it. Ordinary....but inexpensive! I must have been in a good mood or really happy to have a beer. Had a good experience with this. Still though--its super generic.
Pours gold wit ha frothy white head. aroma of malt, grain, corn and small amount of hops. some metallic notes. pretty damn average.

650ml bottle.  pours dark brown with an off-white head. Aroma of malt, chocolate and a bit of alcohol. flavour is very sweet with a fry finish. some coffee and vanilla, slightly artificial flavour. Exceptional.

750ml bottle. 2012 10.5%ABV. pours dark ruby/brown with a frothy off-white head. Aroma of fruit and spice. Powerful and full of flavour with some wheat like character. flavour is fairly sweet and syrupy. Exceeded expectations
750ml bottle. 2012. pours dark brown with a tan almost white head. aroma of malt, dark fruits, caramel and alcohol. flavour is sweet but the alcohol is not all that well balanced. quite nice though.
beer_name: Gouden Carolus Cuvee Van De Keizer Blauw/Blue

review_blob: 500ml bottle. Pours black with a thick brown head. aroma of oats, chocolate, roasted malt, and hops and some caramel. really balanced overall but nothing really stands out as outstanding.

600ml bottle. Pours dark orange with a thin white head. No carbonation. aroma is malt and fruit with some hops, caramel and a hint of vanilla. flavour is sweet and slightly sour. pretty interesting. worth trying
750ml bottle. Pours dark brown with a brown head. Aroma of malt, yeast (but not as much as other Unibroue beers). some dark fruits. flavour is sweet. Slightly sour.

500ml can. Pours clear yellow with very lively carbonation. Creamy white head with surprisingly good retention and strong lacing. Aroma of sweet malt, cardboard and light dry hops. Exceeded my (low) expectations

650ml bottle. Pours dark brown with a hint of red. with a creamy average lasting beige-tan head. Aroma of chocolate, coffee, caramel, and booze. Medium bodied and oily. starts off sweet with a long finish bitter. Nice!

1 L bottle a friend bought. Pours hazy red-orange with a creamy beige head. Aroma of malt, pumpkin, cloves, nutmeg, caramel. An exceptionally well rounded pumpkin beer however it lacks that "special something" to really distinguish it.
beer_name: Howe Sound Pumpkineater Imperial Pumpkin Ale

review_blob: 341 ml bottle from the beer store. Pours dark brown with a small average frothy head. aroma of roasted malt, stale nuts, and a small amount of day old coffee and a little bit of hops. medium bitter medium bodied. Slightly disappointing.
On tap at Hoops at an after-work event downtown. pale gold colour with a small frothy white head. Aroma of fruit, nutmeg, clove. Basically a pumpkin beer without the pumpkin. Not bad.

500ml can. Pours golden yellow, clear with lively carbonation, an average white head with good lacing and okay retention. Aroma of hops, malt, . Taste is crisp with a malty sweetness. some mild bitterness. Not bad, but really nothing special. Its surprisingly decent though.

500ml can. Pours clear yellow with average carbonation. okay lacing and a short lived white head. Aroma is malt, toast, cardboard with some metallic and grainy notes. taste is sweet with a mild and weird sourness to it. Nope.

473ml can 5.5% ABV pours piss yellow with an offputting aroma. Average carbonation and moderately short head retention. Aroma of corn, cereal malt, and some dry coopers yeast. Honestly this tastes like the $20 can of homebrew you can cook up in your microwave.Still beer though...just so many better options....
can.  Pours light yellow with a large, fairly quickly dissipating, white head. flavour is dry-hopps with a lot of sweet malt. Some corn. Nothing special
Can. 5.5%. Pours medium-light amber with a frothy white head with average lacing and rather weak retention. grapefruit/citrus hops. malty. Above average.
can. pours medium-light amber with a slightly below average head. Aroma of hops, mostly citrus hops and minimal grapefruit. Medium bitter. Meh.
beer_name: Double Trouble Hops and Robbers IPA

review_blob: 750ml bottle. Pours dark brown-black. with a large beige head. Aroma of malt, vanilla. moderately sweet with minimal bitterness. incredible long-lasting finish. Overall though its not hing special.
